# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: survival-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] In the statistical area of survival analysis, an **accelerated failure time model** (**AFT model**) is a parametric model that provides an alternative to the commonly used proportional hazards models.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Whereas a proportional hazards model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to multiply the hazard by some constant, an AFT model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to accelerate or decelerate the life course of a disease by some constant.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] There is strong basic science evidence from *C. elegans* experiments by Stroustrup et al. indicating that AFT models are the correct model for biological survival processes.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] where $\theta$ denotes the joint effect of covariates, typically $\theta =\exp(-[\beta _{1}X_{1}+\cdots +\beta _{p}X_{p}])$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] This is satisfied if the probability density function of the event is taken to be $f(t|\theta )=\theta f_{0}(\theta t)$ ; it then follows for the survival function that $S(t|\theta )=S_{0}(\theta t)$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] From this it is easy to see that the moderated life time T is distributed such that $T\theta$ and the unmoderated life time $T_{0}$ have the same distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] where the last term is distributed as $\log(T_{0})$ , i.e., independently of $\theta$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] This reduces the accelerated failure time model to regression analysis (typically a linear model) where $-\log(\theta )$ represents the fixed effects, and $\epsilon$ represents the noise.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Different distributions of $\epsilon$ imply different distributions of $T_{0}$ , i.e., different baseline distributions of the survival time.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Typically, in survival-analytic contexts, many of the observations are censored: we only know that $T_{i}>t_{i}$ , not $T_{i}=t_{i}$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] In fact, the former case represents survival, while the later case represents an event/death/censoring during the follow-up.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] These right-censored observations can pose technical challenges for estimating the model, if the distribution of $T_{0}$ is unusual.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The interpretation of $\theta$ in accelerated failure time models is straightforward: $\theta =2$ means that everything in the relevant life history of an individual happens twice as fast.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, if the model concerns the development of a tumor, it means that all of the pre-stages progress twice as fast as for the unexposed individual, implying that the expected time until a clinical disease is 0.5 of the baseline time.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, this does not mean that the hazard function $\lambda (t|\theta )$ is always twice as high—that would be the proportional hazards model.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike proportional hazards models, in which Cox's semi-parametric proportional hazards model is more widely used than parametric models, AFT models are predominantly fully parametric i.e. a probability distribution is specified for $\log(T_{0})$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hence, technical developments in this direction would be highly desirable.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] When a frailty term is incorporated in the survival model, the regression parameter estimates from AFT models are robust to omitted covariates, unlike proportional hazards models.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] They are also less affected by the choice of probability distribution for the frailty term.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of AFT models are easily interpreted.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, the results of a clinical trial with mortality as the endpoint could be interpreted as a certain percentage increase in future life expectancy on the new treatment compared to the control.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] So a patient could be informed that he would be expected to live (say) 15% longer if he took the new treatment.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hazard ratios can prove harder to explain in layman's terms.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic distribution provides the most commonly used AFT model.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike the Weibull distribution, it can exhibit a non-monotonic hazard function which increases at early times and decreases at later times.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] It is somewhat similar in shape to the log-normal distribution but it has heavier tails.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic cumulative distribution function has a simple closed form, which becomes important computationally when fitting data with censoring.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] For the censored observations one needs the survival function, which is the complement of the cumulative distribution function, i.e. one needs to be able to evaluate $S(t|\theta )=1-F(t|\theta )$ .
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The Weibull distribution (including the exponential distribution as a special case) can be parameterised as either a proportional hazards model or an AFT model, and is the only family of distributions to have this property.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of fitting a Weibull model can therefore be interpreted in either framework.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, the biological applicability of this model may be limited by the fact that the hazard function is monotonic, i.e. either decreasing or increasing.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Any distribution on a multiplicatively closed group, such as the positive real numbers, is suitable for an AFT model.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Other distributions include the log-normal, gamma, hypertabastic, Gompertz distribution, and inverse Gaussian distributions, although they are less popular than the log-logistic, partly as their cumulative distribution functions do not have a closed form.
[src:survival-analysis/accelerated-failure-time-model] Finally, the generalized gamma distribution is a three-parameter distribution that includes the Weibull, log-normal and gamma distributions as special cases.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] In statistics, **censoring** is a condition in which the value of a measurement or observation is only partially known.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] For example, suppose a study is conducted to measure the impact of a drug on mortality rate.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] In such a study, it may be known that an individual's age at death is *at least* 75 years (but may be more).
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Such a situation could occur if the individual withdrew from the study at age 75, or if the individual is currently alive at the age of 75.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Censoring also occurs when a value occurs outside the range of a measuring instrument.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] For example, a bathroom scale might only measure up to 140 kg, after which it rolls over 0 and continues to count up from there.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] If a 160 kg individual is weighed using the scale, the observer would only know that the individual's weight is 20 mod 140 kg (in addition to 160kg, they could weigh 20kg, 300kg, 440kg, and so on).
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] The problem of censored data, in which the observed value of some variable is partially known, is related to the problem of missing data, where the observed value of some variable is unknown.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Censoring should not be confused with the related idea of truncation.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] With censoring, observations result either in knowing the exact value that applies, or in knowing that the value lies within an interval.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] With truncation, observations never result in values outside a given range: values in the population outside the range are never seen or never recorded if they are seen.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Note that in statistics, truncation is not the same as rounding.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Interval censoring can occur when observing a value requires follow-ups or inspections.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Left and right censoring are special cases of interval censoring, with the beginning of the interval at zero or the end at infinity, respectively.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Estimation methods for using left-censored data vary, and not all methods of estimation may be applicable to, or the most reliable, for all data sets.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] A common misconception with time interval data is to class as *left censored* intervals when the start time is unknown.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] In these cases, we have a lower bound on the time *interval*; thus, the data is *right censored* (despite the fact that the missing start point is to the left of the known interval when viewed as a timeline!).
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Special techniques may be used to handle censored data.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Tests with specific failure times are coded as actual failures; censored data are coded for the type of censoring and the known interval or limit.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Special software programs (often reliability oriented) can conduct a maximum likelihood estimation for summary statistics, confidence intervals, etc.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] One of the earliest attempts to analyse a statistical problem involving censored data was Daniel Bernoulli's 1766 analysis of smallpox morbidity and mortality data to demonstrate the efficacy of vaccination.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] An early paper to use the Kaplan–Meier estimator for estimating censored costs was Quesenberry et al.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] (1989), however this approach was found to be invalid by Lin et al. unless all patients accumulated costs with a common deterministic rate function over time, they proposed an alternative estimation technique known as the Lin estimator.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Reliability testing often consists of conducting a test on an item (under specified conditions) to determine the time it takes for a failure to occur.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] An analysis of the data from replicate tests includes both the times-to-failure for the items that failed and the time-of-test-termination for those that did not fail.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] An earlier model for censored regression, the tobit model, was proposed by James Tobin in 1958.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] The likelihood is the probability or probability density of what was observed, viewed as a function of parameters in an assumed model.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] To incorporate censored data points in the likelihood the censored data points are represented by the probability of the censored data points as a function of the model parameters given a model, i.e. a function of CDF(s) instead of the density or probability mass.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] Suppose we are interested in survival times, $T_{1},T_{2},\dots ,T_{n}$ , but we don't observe $T_{i}$ for all i .
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] where $f(u_{i})$ is the probability density function evaluated at $u_{i}$ , and $S(u_{i})$ is the probability that $T_{i}$ is greater than $u_{i}$ , called the *survival function*.
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] For the exponential distribution, this becomes even simpler, because the hazard rate, $\lambda$ , is constant, and $S(u)=\exp(-\lambda u)$ .
[src:survival-analysis/censoring-statistics] This differs from the standard MLE for the exponential distribution in that the censored observations are considered only in the numerator.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In real-world applications, the failure probability of a system usually differs over time; failures occur more frequently in early-life ("burning in"), or as a system ages ("wearing out").
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This is known as the bathtub curve, where the middle region is called the "useful life period".
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The mean time between failures (MTBF, $1/\lambda$ ) is often reported instead of the failure rate, as numbers such as "2,000 hours" are more intuitive than numbers such as "0.0005 per hour".
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] However, this is only valid if the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is actually constant over time, such as within the flat region of the bathtub curve.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In many cases where MTBF is quoted, it refers only to this region; thus it cannot be used to give an accurate calculation of the average lifetime of a system, as it ignores the "burn-in" and "wear-out" regions.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] MTBF appears frequently in engineering design requirements, and governs the frequency of required system maintenance and inspections.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] A similar ratio used in the transport industries, especially in railways and trucking, is "mean distance between failures" (MDBF) - allowing maintenance to be scheduled based on distance travelled, rather than at regular time intervals.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] which would depend on the number of systems under study, and the conditions over the time period.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] To accurately model failures over time, a **cumulative failure distribution**, $F(t)$ must be defined, which can be any cumulative distribution function (CDF) that gradually increases from 0 to 1 .
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] where $\tau$ is a dummy integration variable.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] A concept closely related but different to instantaneous failure rate $f(t)$ is the **hazard rate** (or **hazard function**), $h(t)$ .
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In the many-system case, this is defined as the proportional failure rate of the systems *still functioning* at time t – as opposed to $f(t)$ , which is the expressed as a proportion of the *initial number* of systems.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Thus for a collection of identical systems, only one of hazard rate $h(t)$ , failure probability density $f(t)$ , or cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ need be defined.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] an exponential function with scaling constant $\lambda$ .
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] As seen in the figures above, this represents a gradually decreasing failure probability density.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] which can be seen to gradually approach 1 as $t\to \infty ,$ representing the fact that eventually all systems under study will fail.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In other words, in this particular case *only*, the hazard rate is constant over time.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This illustrates the difference in hazard rate and failure probability density - as the number of systems surviving at time $t>0$ gradually reduces, the total failure rate also reduces, but the hazard rate **remains constant**.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In other words, the probabilities of each individual system failing do not change over time as the systems age - they are "memory-less".
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For many systems, a constant hazard function may not be a realistic approximation; the chance of failure of an individual component may depend on its age.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Therefore, other distributions are often used.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For example, the deterministic distribution increases hazard rate over time (for systems where wear-out is the most important factor), while the Pareto distribution decreases it (for systems where early-life failures are more common).
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The commonly used Weibull distribution combines both of these effects, as do the log-normal and hypertabastic distributions.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] After modelling a given distribution and parameters for $h(t)$ , the failure probability density $f(t)$ and cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ can be predicted using the given equations.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Failure rate data can be obtained in several ways.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] From field failure rate reports, statistical analysis techniques can be used to estimate failure rates.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For accurate failure rates the analyst must have a good understanding of equipment operation, procedures for data collection, the key environmental variables impacting failure rates, how the equipment is used at the system level, and how the failure data will be used by system designers.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Many organizations maintain internal databases of failure information on the devices or systems that they produce, which can be used to calculate failure rates for those devices or systems.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For new devices or systems, the historical data for similar devices or systems can serve as a useful estimate.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Handbooks of failure rate data for various components are available from government and commercial sources.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] that provides failure rate data for many military electronic components.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Several failure rate data sources are available commercially that focus on commercial components, including some non-electronic components.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Time lag is one of the serious drawbacks of all failure rate estimations.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Often by the time the failure rate data are available, the devices under study have become obsolete.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Due to this drawback, failure-rate prediction methods have been developed.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] These methods may be used on newly designed devices to predict the device's failure rates and failure modes.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Two approaches have become well known, Cycle Testing and FMEDA.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The most accurate source of data is to test samples of the actual devices or systems in order to generate failure data.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This is often prohibitively expensive or impractical, so that the previous data sources are often used instead.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Mechanical movement is the predominant failure mechanism causing mechanical and electromechanical devices to wear out.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For many devices, the wear-out failure point is measured by the number of cycles performed before the device fails, and can be discovered by cycle testing.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In cycle testing, a device is cycled as rapidly as practical until it fails.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] When a collection of these devices are tested, the test will run until 10% of the units fail dangerously.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] (FMEDA) is a systematic analysis technique to obtain subsystem / product level failure rates, failure modes and design strength.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Given a component database calibrated with field failure data that is reasonably accurate, the method can predict product level failure rate and failure mode data for a given application.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The predictions have been shown to be more accurate than field warranty return analysis or even typical field failure analysis given that these methods depend on reports that typically do not have sufficient detail information in failure records.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] A decreasing failure rate describes cases where early-life failures are common and corresponds to the situation where $h(t)$ is a decreasing function.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This can describe, for example, the period of infant mortality in humans, or the early failure of transistors due to manufacturing defects.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The hazard rate of aircraft air conditioning systems was found to have an exponentially decreasing distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] In special processes called renewal processes, where the time to recover from failure can be neglected, the likelihood of failure remains constant with respect to time.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For a renewal process with DFR renewal function, inter-renewal times are concave.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Brown conjectured the converse, that DFR is also necessary for the inter-renewal times to be concave, however it has been shown that this conjecture holds neither in the discrete case nor in the continuous case.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] When the failure rate is decreasing the coefficient of variation is ⩾ 1, and when the failure rate is increasing the coefficient of variation is ⩽ 1.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Note that this result only holds when the failure rate is defined for all t ⩾ 0 and that the converse result (coefficient of variation determining nature of failure rate) does not hold.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Failure rates can be expressed using any measure of time, but **hours** is the most common unit in practice.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Other units, such as miles, revolutions, etc., can also be used in place of "time" units.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Failure rates are often expressed in engineering notation as failures per million, or 10−6, especially for individual components, since their failure rates are often very low.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] The **Failures In Time** (**FIT**) rate of a device is the number of failures that can be expected in one billion (109) device-hours of operation (e.g.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This term is used particularly by the semiconductor industry.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] however, this assumes that the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is constant, and that the units are consistent (e.g. failures per million hours), and not expressed as a ratio or as probability densities.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] This is useful to estimate the failure rate of a system when individual components or subsystems have already been tested.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] When adding "redundant" components to eliminate a single point of failure, the quantity of interest is not the sum of individual failure rates but rather the "mission failure" rate, or the "mean time between critical failures" (MTBCF).
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Combining failure or hazard rates that are time-dependent is more complicated.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] For example, mixtures of Decreasing Failure Rate (DFR) variables are also DFR.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Mixtures of exponentially distributed failure rates are hyperexponentially distributed.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Suppose it is desired to estimate the failure rate of a certain component.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] Ten identical components are each tested until they either fail or reach 1,000 hours, at which time the test is terminated.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] A total of 7,502 component-hours of testing is performed, and 6 failures are recorded.
[src:survival-analysis/failure-rate] which could also be expressed as a MTBF of 1,250 hours, or approximately 800 failures for every million hours of operation.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In actuarial science and demography, a **life table** (also called a **mortality table** or **actuarial table**) is a table which shows, for each age, the probability that a person of that age will die before their next birthday ("probability of death").
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In other words, it represents the survivorship of people from a certain population.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] They can also be explained as a long-term mathematical way to measure a population's longevity.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Tables have been created by demographers including John Graunt, Reed and Merrell, Nathan Keyfitz, and Thomas N.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] There are two types of life tables used in actuarial science.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The period life table represents mortality rates during a specific time period for a certain population.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] A cohort life table, often referred to as a generation life table, is used to represent the overall mortality rates of a certain population's entire lifetime.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] They must have had to be born during the same specific time interval.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] A cohort life table is more frequently used because it is able to make a prediction of any expected changes in the mortality rates of a population in the future.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] This type of table also analyzes patterns in mortality rates that can be observed over time.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Both of these types of life tables are created based on an actual population from the present, as well as an educated prediction of the experience of a population in the near future.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In order to find the true life expectancy average, 100 years would need to pass and by then finding that data would be of no use as healthcare is continually advancing.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Other life tables in historical demography may be based on historical records, although these often undercount infants and understate infant mortality, on comparison with other regions with better records, and on mathematical adjustments for varying mortality levels and life expectancies at birth.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] From this starting point, a number of inferences can be derived.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Life tables are also used extensively in biology and epidemiology.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] An area that uses this tool is Social Security.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] It examines the mortality rates of all the people who have Social Security to decide which actions to take.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The concept is also of importance in product life cycle management.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] All mortality tables are specific to environmental and life circumstances, and are used to probabilistically determine expected maximum age within those environmental conditions.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] allows study of life expectancy as a function of age already achieved.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Static life tables sample individuals assuming a stationary population with overlapping generations.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] "Static life tables" and "cohort life tables" will be identical if population is in equilibrium and environment does not change.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] If a population were to have a constant number of people each year, it would mean that the probabilities of death from the life table were completely accurate.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Also, an exact number of 100,000 people were born each year with no immigration or emigration involved.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] "Life table" primarily refers to *period* life tables, as cohort life tables can only be constructed using data up to the current point, and distant projections for future mortality.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Life tables can be constructed using projections of future mortality rates, but more often they are a snapshot of age-specific mortality rates in the recent past, and do not necessarily purport to be projections.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] A life table is created by mortality rates and census figures from a certain population, ideally under a closed demographic system.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] This means that immigration and emigration do not exist when analyzing a cohort.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] A closed demographic system assumes that migration flows are random and not significant, and that immigrants from other populations have the same risk of death as an individual from the new population.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Another benefit from mortality tables is that they can be used to make predictions on demographics or different populations.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] However, there are also weaknesses of the information displayed on life tables.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] One being that they do not state the overall health of the population.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] There is more than one disease present in the world, and a person can have more than one disease at different stages simultaneously, introducing the term comorbidity.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Therefore, life tables also do not show the direct correlation of mortality and morbidity.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The life table observes the mortality experience of a single generation, consisting of 100,000 births, at every age number they can live through.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Life tables are usually constructed separately for men and for women because of their substantially different mortality rates.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Other characteristics can also be used to distinguish different risks, such as smoking status, occupation, and socioeconomic class.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Life tables can be extended to include other information in addition to mortality, for instance health information to calculate health expectancy.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Health expectancies such as disability-adjusted life year and Healthy Life Years are the remaining number of years a person can expect to live in a specific health state, such as free of disability.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Life tables that relate to maternal deaths and infant moralities are important, as they help form family planning programs that work with particular populations.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] They also help compare a country's average life expectancy with other countries.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Comparing life expectancy globally helps countries understand why one country's life expectancy is rising substantially by looking at each other's healthcare, and adopting ideas to their own systems.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In order to price insurance products, and ensure the solvency of insurance companies through adequate reserves, actuaries must develop projections of future insured events (such as death, sickness, and disability).
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] To do this, actuaries develop mathematical models of the rates and timing of the events.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] An actuary's job is to form a comparison between people at risk of death and people who actually died to come up with a probability of death for a person at each age number, defined as qx in an equation.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] When analyzing a population, one of the main sources used to gather the required information is insurance by obtaining individual records that belong to a specific population.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] These are called mortality tables if they show death rates, and morbidity tables if they show various types of sickness or disability rates.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] This is particularly the case in non-life insurance (e.g. the pricing of motor insurance can allow for a large number of risk factors, which requires a correspondingly complex table of expected claim rates).
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] However the expression "life table" normally refers to human survival rates and is not relevant to non-life insurance.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The basic algebra used in life tables is as follows.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] This symbol refers to central rate of mortality.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] It is approximately equal to the average force of mortality, averaged over the year of age.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Further descriptions: The variable dx stands for the number of deaths that would occur within two consecutive age numbers.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] An example of this is the number of deaths in a cohort that were recorded between the age of seven and the age of eight.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The variable *ℓx*, which stands for the opposite of *dx*, represents the number of people who lived between two consecutive age numbers.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The variable *Tx* stands for the years lived beyond each age number x by all members in the generation.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] *Ėx* represents the life expectancy for members already at a specific age number.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In practice, it is useful to have an ultimate age associated with a mortality table.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Once the ultimate age is reached, the mortality rate is assumed to be 1.000.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] This age may be the point at which life insurance benefits are paid to a survivor or annuity payments cease.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] In epidemiology and public health, both standard life tables (used to calculate life expectancy), as well as the Sullivan and multi-state life tables (used to calculate health expectancy)**,** are the most commonly mathematical used devices.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] The latter includes information on health in addition to mortality.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] By watching over the life expectancy of any year(s) being studied, epidemiologists can see if diseases are contributing to the overall increase in mortality rates.
[src:survival-analysis/life-table] Epidemiologists are able to help demographers understand the sudden decline of life expectancy by linking it to the health problems that are arising in certain populations.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] To answer such questions, it is necessary to define "lifetime".
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the case of biological survival, death is unambiguous, but for mechanical reliability, failure may not be well-defined, for there may well be mechanical systems in which failure is partial, a matter of degree, or not otherwise localized in time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Even in biological problems, some events (for example, heart attack or other organ failure) may have the same ambiguity.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The theory outlined below assumes well-defined events at specific times; other cases may be better treated by models which explicitly account for ambiguous events.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] More generally, survival analysis involves the modelling of time to event data; in this context, death or failure is considered an "event" in the survival analysis literature – traditionally only a single event occurs for each subject, after which the organism or mechanism is dead or broken.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] *Recurring event* or *repeated event* models relax that assumption.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The study of recurring events is relevant in systems reliability, and in many areas of social sciences and medical research.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This example uses the Acute Myelogenous Leukemia survival data set "aml" from the "survival" package in R.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The data set is from Miller (1997) and the question is whether the standard course of chemotherapy should be extended ('maintained') for additional cycles.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The aml data set sorted by survival time is shown in the box.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The last observation (11), at 161 weeks, is censored.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Censoring indicates that the patient did not have an event (no recurrence of aml cancer).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Another subject, observation 3, was censored at 13 weeks (indicated by status=0).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This subject was in the study for only 13 weeks, and the aml cancer did not recur during those 13 weeks.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It is possible that this patient was enrolled near the end of the study, so that they could be observed for only 13 weeks.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It is also possible that the patient was enrolled early in the study, but was lost to follow up or withdrew from the study.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The table shows that other subjects were censored at 16, 28, and 45 weeks (observations 17, 6, and 9 with status=0).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The remaining subjects all experienced events (recurrence of aml cancer) while in the study.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The question of interest is whether recurrence occurs later in maintained patients than in non-maintained patients.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The survival function *S*(*t*), is the probability that a subject survives longer than time *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] *S*(*t*) is theoretically a smooth curve, but it is usually estimated using the Kaplan–Meier (KM) curve.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] A life table summarizes survival data in terms of the number of events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The life table for the aml data, created using the R software, is shown.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The life table summarizes the events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log-rank test compares the survival times of two or more groups.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This example uses a log-rank test for a difference in survival in the maintained versus non-maintained treatment groups in the aml data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The graph shows KM plots for the aml data broken out by treatment group, which is indicated by the variable "x" in the data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The null hypothesis for a log-rank test is that the groups have the same survival.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The expected number of subjects surviving at each time point in each is adjusted for the number of subjects at risk in the groups at each event time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log-rank test determines if the observed number of events in each group is significantly different from the expected number.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The formal test is based on a chi-squared statistic.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] When the log-rank statistic is large, it is evidence for a difference in the survival times between the groups.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log-rank statistic approximately has a Chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom, and the p-value is calculated using the Chi-squared test.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For the example data, the log-rank test for difference in survival gives a p-value of p=0.0653, indicating that the treatment groups do not differ significantly in survival, assuming an alpha level of 0.05.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The sample size of 23 subjects is modest, so there is little power to detect differences between the treatment groups.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The chi-squared test is based on asymptotic approximation, so the p-value should be regarded with caution for small sample sizes.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Kaplan–Meier curves and log-rank tests are most useful when the predictor variable is categorical (e.g., drug vs. placebo), or takes a small number of values (e.g., drug doses 0, 20, 50, and 100 mg/day) that can be treated as categorical.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log-rank test and KM curves don't work easily with quantitative predictors such as gene expression, white blood count, or age.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For quantitative predictor variables, an alternative method is Cox proportional hazards regression analysis.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Cox PH models work also with categorical predictor variables, which are encoded as {0,1} indicator or dummy variables.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH analysis, and can be performed using Cox PH software.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set from Dalgaard Chapter 14.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox proportional hazards regression using R gives the results shown in the box.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox regression results are interpreted as follows.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The summary output also gives upper and lower 95% confidence intervals for the hazard ratio: lower 95% bound = 1.15; upper 95% bound = 3.26.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] These three tests are asymptotically equivalent.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For large enough N, they will give similar results.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The last row, "Score (logrank) test" is the result for the log-rank test, with p=0.011, the same result as the log-rank test, because the log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH regression.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Likelihood ratio test has better behavior for small sample sizes, so it is generally preferred.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox model extends the log-rank test by allowing the inclusion of additional covariates.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set where the predictor variables include a continuous covariate, the thickness of the tumor (variable name = "thick").
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the histograms, the thickness values are positively skewed and do not have a Gaussian-like, symmetric probability distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Regression models, including the Cox model, generally give more reliable results with normally-distributed variables.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For this example we may use a logarithmic transform.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The log of the thickness of the tumor looks to be more normally distributed, so the Cox models will use log thickness.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox PH analysis using R gives the results below.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The p-value for all three overall tests (likelihood, Wald, and score) are significant, indicating that the model is significant.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The p-value for $\log({\text{thick}})$ is 6.94×10−7, with a hazard ratio $HR=\exp({\text{coef}})=2.183$ , indicating a strong relationship between the thickness of the tumor and increased risk of death.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Because the confidence interval for HR includes 1, these results indicate that sex makes a smaller contribution to the difference in the HR after controlling for the thickness of the tumor.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Examination of graphs of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex and a t-test of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex both indicate that there is a significant difference between men and women in the thickness of the tumor when they first see the clinician.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox model assumes that the hazards are proportional.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The proportional hazard assumption may be tested using the R function `cox.zph()` from the survival R package.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] A p-value which is less than 0.05 indicates that the hazards are not proportional.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For the melanoma data, we obtain $p=0.248$ for sex.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Hence, we cannot reject the null hypothesis of the hazards of sex being proportional.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Cox models can be extended to deal with variations on the simple analysis.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Cox PH regression model is a linear model.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It is similar to linear regression and logistic regression.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Specifically, these methods assume that a single line, curve, plane, or surface is sufficient to separate groups (alive, dead) or to estimate a quantitative response (survival time).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In some cases alternative partitions give more accurate classification or quantitative estimates.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] One set of alternative methods are tree-structured survival models, including survival random forests.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Tree-structured survival models may give more accurate predictions than Cox models.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Examining both types of models for a given data set is a reasonable strategy.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This example of a survival tree analysis uses the R package "rpart".
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The example is based on 146 stage C prostate cancer patients in the data set stagec in rpart.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Rpart and the stagec example are described in Atkinson and Therneau (1997), which is also distributed as a vignette of the rpart package.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The survival tree produced by the analysis is shown in the figure.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Each branch in the tree indicates a split on the value of a variable.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For example, the root of the tree splits subjects with grade < 2.5 versus subjects with grade 2.5 or greater.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The terminal nodes indicate the number of subjects in the node, the number of subjects who have events, and the relative event rate compared to the root.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the node on the far left, the values 1/33 indicate that one of the 33 subjects in the node had an event, and that the relative event rate is 0.122.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the node on the far right bottom, the values 11/15 indicate that 11 of 15 subjects in the node had an event, and the relative event rate is 2.7.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] An alternative to building a single survival tree is to build many survival trees, where each tree is constructed using a sample of the data, and average the trees to predict survival.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This is the method underlying the survival random forest models.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Survival random forest analysis is available in the R package "randomForestSRC".
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The randomForestSRC package includes an example survival random forest analysis using the data set pbc.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This data is from the Mayo Clinic Primary Biliary Cirrhosis (PBC) trial of the liver conducted between 1974 and 1984.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the example, the random forest survival model gives more accurate predictions of survival than the Cox PH model.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The prediction errors are estimated by bootstrap re-sampling.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Recent advancements in deep representation learning have been extended to survival estimation.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The DeepSurv model proposes to replace the log-linear parameterization of the CoxPH model with a multi-layer perceptron.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Further extensions like Deep Survival Machines and Deep Cox Mixtures involve the use of latent variable mixture models to model the time-to-event distribution as a mixture of parametric or semi-parametric distributions while jointly learning representations of the input covariates.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Deep learning approaches have shown superior performance especially on complex input data modalities such as images and clinical time-series.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The object of primary interest is the **survival function**, conventionally denoted *S*, which is defined as $S(t)=\Pr(T>t)$ where *t* is some time, *T* is a random variable denoting the time of death, or more generally any event, and "Pr" stands for probability.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] That is, the survival function is the probability of observing an event time greater than some specified time *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The survival function is also called the *survivor function* or *survivorship function* in problems of biological survival, and the *reliability function* in mechanical survival problems.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the latter case, the reliability function is denoted *R*(*t*).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Usually one assumes *S*(0) = 1, although it could be less than 1 if there is the possibility of immediate death or failure.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The survival function must be non-increasing: *S*(*u*) ≤ *S*(*t*) if *u* ≥ *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This property follows directly because *T*>*u* implies *T*>*t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This reflects the notion that survival to a later age is possible only if all younger ages are attained.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Given this property, the lifetime distribution function and event density (*F* and *f* below) are well-defined.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The survival function is usually assumed to approach zero as age increases without bound (i.e., *S*(*t*) → 0 as *t* → ∞), although the limit could be greater than zero if eternal life is possible.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For instance, we could apply survival analysis to a mixture of stable and unstable carbon isotopes; unstable isotopes would decay sooner or later, but the stable isotopes would last indefinitely.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Related quantities are defined in terms of the survival function.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] $f(t)=F'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}F(t).$ The function *f* is sometimes called the **event density**; it is the rate of death or failure events per unit time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] $s(t)=S'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}S(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}\int _{t}^{\infty }f(u)\,du={\frac {d}{dt}}[1-F(t)]=-f(t).$ In other fields, such as statistical physics, the survival event density function is known as the first passage time density.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Synonyms for *hazard function* in different fields include hazard rate, intensity function, force of mortality (demography and actuarial science, denoted by $\mu$ ), force of failure, or failure rate (engineering, denoted $\lambda$ ).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For example, in actuarial science, $\mu (x)$ denotes rate of death for people aged x , whereas in reliability engineering $\lambda (t)$ denotes rate of failure of components after operation for time t .
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The hazard function represents the probability that a subject will experience an event in the next small interval of time, divided by the length of this interval, given that they have survived up to time t .
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] where Bayes' theorem, and identifying $\Pr(T>t)$ as the survival function, has been used in the first equality, and the definition of the density function of the lifetime distribution in the second.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In fact, the hazard rate is usually more informative about the underlying mechanism of failure than the other representations of a lifetime distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The hazard function must be non-negative, $\lambda (t)\geq 0$ , and its integral over $[0,\infty ]$ must be infinite, but is not otherwise constrained; it may be increasing or decreasing, non-monotonic, or discontinuous.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] An example is the bathtub curve hazard function, which is large for small values of t , decreasing to some minimum, and thereafter increasing again; this can model the property of some mechanical systems to either fail soon after operation, or much later, as the system ages.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] $\Lambda (t)=\int _{0}^{t}\lambda (u)\,du$ which is the "accumulation" of the hazard over time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] From the definition of $\Lambda (t)$ , we see that it increases without bound as *t* tends to infinity (assuming that $S(t)$ tends to zero).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This implies that $\lambda (t)$ must not decrease too quickly, since, by definition, the cumulative hazard has to diverge.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For example, $\exp(-t)$ is not the hazard function of any survival distribution, because its integral converges to 1.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For $t_{0}=0$ , that is, at birth, this reduces to the expected lifetime.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In reliability problems, the expected lifetime is called the *mean time to failure*, and the expected future lifetime is called the *mean residual lifetime*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] As the probability of an individual surviving until age *t* or later is *S*(*t*), by definition, the expected number of survivors at age *t* out of an initial population of *n* newborns is *n* × *S*(*t*), assuming the same survival function for all individuals.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Thus the expected proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] If the survival of different individuals is independent, the number of survivors at age *t* has a binomial distribution with parameters *n* and *S*(*t*), and the variance of the proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*) × (1-*S*(*t*))/*n*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The age at which a specified proportion of survivors remain can be found by solving the equation *S*(*t*) = *q* for *t*, where *q* is the quantile in question.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Typically one is interested in the **median lifetime**, for which *q* = 1/2, or other quantiles such as *q* = 0.90 or *q* = 0.99.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Censoring is a form of missing data problem in which time to event is not observed for reasons such as termination of study before all recruited subjects have shown the event of interest or the subject has left the study prior to experiencing an event.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Censoring is common in survival analysis.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] If only the lower limit *l* for the true event time *T* is known such that *T* > *l*, this is called *right censoring*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Right censoring will occur, for example, for those subjects whose birth date is known but who are still alive when they are lost to follow-up or when the study ends.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] We generally encounter right-censored data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] If the event of interest has already happened before the subject is included in the study but it is not known when it occurred, the data is said to be *left-censored*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] When it can only be said that the event happened between two observations or examinations, this is *interval censoring*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Left censoring occurs for example when a permanent tooth has already emerged prior to the start of a dental study that aims to estimate its emergence distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In the same study, an emergence time is interval-censored when the permanent tooth is present in the mouth at the current examination but not yet at the previous examination.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Interval censoring often occurs in HIV/AIDS studies.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Indeed, time to HIV seroconversion can be determined only by a laboratory assessment which is usually initiated after a visit to the physician.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Then one can only conclude that HIV seroconversion has happened between two examinations.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The same is true for the diagnosis of AIDS, which is based on clinical symptoms and needs to be confirmed by a medical examination.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It may also happen that subjects with a lifetime less than some threshold may not be observed at all: this is called *truncation*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Note that truncation is different from left censoring, since for a left censored datum, we know the subject exists, but for a truncated datum, we may be completely unaware of the subject.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In a so-called *delayed entry* study, subjects are not observed at all until they have reached a certain age.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For example, people may not be observed until they have reached the age to enter school.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Any deceased subjects in the pre-school age group would be unknown.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Left-truncated data are common in actuarial work for life insurance and pensions.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Left-censored data can occur when a person's survival time becomes incomplete on the left side of the follow-up period for the person.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] For example, in an epidemiological example, we may monitor a patient for an infectious disorder starting from the time when he or she is tested positive for the infection.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Although we may know the right-hand side of the duration of interest, we may never know the exact time of exposure to the infectious agent.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Survival models can be usefully viewed as ordinary regression models in which the response variable is time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] However, computing the likelihood function (needed for fitting parameters or making other kinds of inferences) is complicated by the censoring.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The likelihood function for a survival model, in the presence of censored data, is formulated as follows.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] By definition the likelihood function is the conditional probability of the data given the parameters of the model.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It is customary to assume that the data are independent given the parameters.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Then the likelihood function is the product of the likelihood of each datum.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] It is convenient to partition the data into four categories: uncensored, left censored, right censored, and interval censored.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] These are denoted "unc.", "l.c.", "r.c.", and "i.c." in the equation below.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Kaplan–Meier estimator can be used to estimate the survival function.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The Nelson–Aalen estimator can be used to provide a non-parametric estimate of the cumulative hazard rate function.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make nonparametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] While many parametric models assume a continuous-time, discrete-time survival models can be mapped to a binary classification problem.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] In a discrete-time survival model the survival period is artificially resampled in intervals where for each interval a binary target indicator is recorded if the event takes place in a certain time horizon.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] If a binary classifier (potentially enhanced with a different likelihood to take more structure of the problem into account) is calibrated, then the classifier score is the hazard function (i.e. the conditional probability of failure).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Discrete-time survival models are connected to empirical likelihood.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Instead of performing the time-discretization and bringing the data in this long-format, an alternative way is to perform distributional regression over the binned time-axis.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This approach can leverage prior data fitted networks (tabular foundation models) to work with small data sets already.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The goodness of fit of survival models can be assessed using scoring rules.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] A cure model allows for the possibility that some individuals never experience the event of interest.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] This creates survival curves that plateau rather than always converging to zero.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] First term: cured individuals, who survive indefinitely.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Second term: susceptible individuals, whose survival declines according to the hazard.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] Without a cure model, survival is forced to zero in the limit of large times.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The textbook by Kleinbaum has examples of survival analyses using SAS, R, and other packages.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-analysis] The textbooks by Brostrom, Dalgaard and Tableman and Kim give examples of survival analyses using R (or using S, and which run in R).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The **survival function** is a function that gives the probability that a patient, device, or other object of interest will survive past a certain time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The survival function is also known as the **survivor function** or **reliability function**.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The term *reliability function* is common in engineering while the term *survival function* is used in a broader range of applications, including human mortality.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function of the lifetime.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Sometimes complementary cumulative distribution functions are called survival functions in general.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Let the lifetime T be a continuous random variable describing the time to failure.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The graphs below show examples of hypothetical survival functions.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The *y*-axis is the proportion of subjects surviving.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The graphs show the probability that a subject will survive beyond time *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For example, for survival function 1, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.37.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] That is, 37% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For survival function 2, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.97.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] That is, 97% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Median survival may be determined from the survival function: The median survival is the point where the survival function intersects the value 0.5.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For example, for survival function 2, 50% of the subjects survive 3.72 months.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Median survival cannot always be determined from the graph alone.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For example, in survival function 4, more than 50% of the subjects survive longer than the observation period of 10 months.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The survival function is one of several ways to describe and display survival data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Another useful way to display data is a graph showing the distribution of survival times of subjects.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Olkin, page 426, gives the following example of survival data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The number of hours between successive failures of an air-conditioning (AC) system were recorded.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The figure below shows the distribution of the time between failures.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The blue tick marks beneath the graph are the actual hours between successive AC failures.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In this example, a curve representing the exponential distribution overlays the distribution of AC failure times; the exponential distribution approximates the distribution of AC failure times.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The distribution of failure times is the probability density function (PDF), since time can take any positive value.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In equations, the PDF is specified as *fT*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] If time can only take discrete values (such as 1 day, 2 days, and so on), the distribution of failure times is called the probability mass function.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Most survival analysis methods assume that time can take any positive value, and *fT* is the PDF.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] If the time between observed AC failures is approximated using the exponential function, then the exponential curve gives the probability density function, *fT*, for AC failure times.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Another useful way to display the survival data is a graph showing the cumulative failures up to each time point.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] These data may be displayed as either the cumulative number or the cumulative proportion of failures up to each time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The graph below shows the cumulative probability (or proportion) of failures at each time for the air conditioning system.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The stairstep line in black shows the cumulative proportion of failures.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For each step there is a blue tick at the bottom of the graph indicating an observed failure time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The smooth red line represents the exponential curve fitted to the observed data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] A graph of the cumulative probability of failures up to each time point is called the cumulative distribution function (CDF).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In survival analysis, the cumulative distribution function gives the probability that the survival time is less than or equal to a specific time, *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Let *T* be survival time, which is any positive number.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] A particular time is designated by the lower case letter *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] where the right-hand side represents the probability that the random variable *T* is less than or equal to *t*.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] If time can take on any positive value, then the cumulative distribution function *F*(*t*) is the integral of the probability density function *f*(*t*).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For the air-conditioning example, the graph of the CDF below illustrates that the probability that the time to failure is less than or equal to 100 hours is 0.81, as estimated using the exponential curve fit to the data.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] An alternative to graphing the probability that the failure time is *less* than or equal to 100 hours is to graph the probability that the failure time is *greater* than 100 hours.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The probability that the failure time is greater than 100 hours must be 1 minus the probability that the failure time is less than or equal to 100 hours, because total probability must sum to 1.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] This relationship is shown on the graphs below.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The graph on the left is the cumulative distribution function, which is Pr(*T* ≤ *t*).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The graph on the right is the survival function, *S*(*t*).
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The fact that the *S*(*t*) = 1 – CDF is the reason that another name for the survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In some cases, such as the air conditioner example, the distribution of survival times may be approximated well by a function such as the exponential distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Several distributions are commonly used in survival analysis, including the exponential, Weibull, gamma, normal, log-normal, and log-logistic.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] These distributions are defined by parameters.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The normal (Gaussian) distribution, for example, is defined by the two parameters mean and standard deviation.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Survival functions that are defined by parameters are said to be parametric.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For an exponential survival distribution, the probability of failure is the same in every time interval, no matter the age of the individual or device.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] This fact leads to the "memoryless" property of the exponential survival distribution: the age of a subject has no effect on the probability of failure in the next time interval.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The exponential may be a good model for the lifetime of a system where parts are replaced as they fail.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] It may also be useful for modeling survival of living organisms over short intervals.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] It is not likely to be a good model of the complete lifespan of a living organism.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] 134) note, "If human lifetimes were exponential there wouldn't be old or young people, just lucky or unlucky ones".
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] A key assumption of the exponential survival function is that the hazard rate is constant.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In an example given above, the proportion of men dying each year was constant at 10%, meaning that the hazard rate was constant.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The assumption of constant hazard may not be appropriate.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For example, among most living organisms, the risk of death is greater in old age than in middle age – that is, the hazard rate increases with time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] For some diseases, such as breast cancer, the risk of recurrence is lower after 5 years – that is, the hazard rate decreases with time.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The Weibull distribution extends the exponential distribution to allow constant, increasing, or decreasing hazard rates.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] There are several other parametric survival functions that may provide a better fit to a particular data set, including normal, lognormal, log-logistic, and gamma.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] The choice of parametric distribution for a particular application can be made using graphical methods or using formal tests of fit.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] These distributions and tests are described in textbooks on survival analysis.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Lawless has extensive coverage of parametric models.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Parametric survival functions are commonly used in manufacturing applications, in part because they enable estimation of the survival function beyond the observation period.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] However, appropriate use of parametric functions requires that data are well modeled by the chosen distribution.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] If an appropriate distribution is not available, or cannot be specified before a clinical trial or experiment, then non-parametric survival functions offer a useful alternative.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] A parametric model of survival may not be possible or desirable.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] In these situations, the most common method to model the survival function is the non-parametric Kaplan–Meier estimator.
[src:survival-analysis/survival-function] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make non-parametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
